T1  - Product Market Competition and Internal Governance: Evidence from the Sarbanes–Oxley Act
AU  - Chhaochharia, Vidhi
AU  - Grinstein, Yaniv
AU  - Grullon, Gustavo
AU  - Michaely, Roni
Y1  - 2016/05/19
PY  - 2016
DA  - 2017/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2015.2409
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2015.2409
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1405
EP  - 1424
VL  - 63
IS  - 5
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - We use the Sarbanes?Oxley Act of 2002 (SOX) as a quasi-natural experiment to examine the link between product market competition and internal governance mechanisms. Consistent with the notion that competition plays an important role in aligning incentives within the firm, SOX has led to a larger improvement in the operation of firms in concentrated industries than in nonconcentrated industries. Furthermore, within concentrated industries, the effect is especially pronounced among firms with weaker governance mechanisms prior to SOX. We corroborate these findings using two additional regulatory changes in the United States and abroad. Overall, our results indicate that corporate governance is more important when firms face less product market competition. This paper was accepted by Itay Goldstein, finance.
AB  - We use the Sarbanes?Oxley Act of 2002 (SOX) as a quasi-natural experiment to examine the link between product market competition and internal governance mechanisms. Consistent with the notion that competition plays an important role in aligning incentives within the firm, SOX has led to a larger improvement in the operation of firms in concentrated industries than in nonconcentrated industries. Furthermore, within concentrated industries, the effect is especially pronounced among firms with weaker governance mechanisms prior to SOX. We corroborate these findings using two additional regulatory changes in the United States and abroad. Overall, our results indicate that corporate governance is more important when firms face less product market competition. This paper was accepted by Itay Goldstein, finance.
